hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a homogeneous, isotropic, isothermal, small-strain porous solid described by a Helmholtz free energy density per unit reference volume $\,\psi(\varepsilon, m)\,$, where $\,\varepsilon\,$ is the infinitesimal strain tensor and $\,m\,$ is the fluid content per reference volume. Use the standard thermodynamic structure for isothermal processes, in which the thermodynamic forces conjugate to $\,\varepsilon\,$ and $\,m\,$ are obtained from $\,\psi\,$ by appropriate derivatives, and the Clausius–Duhem inequality reduces to a constitutive restriction on $\,\psi\,$. Work at a reference state $\,(\varepsilon, m) = (\mathbf{0}, 0)\,$ and consider linearized increments about this state.

Define the Biot coupling coefficient $\,\alpha\,$ and Biot modulus $\,M\,$ by the linearized fluid-content relation at fixed temperature
$$
dm \;=\; \alpha\, d(\operatorname{tr}\varepsilon) \;+\; \frac{1}{M}\, dp,
$$
where $\,p\,$ denotes the pore pressure, and $\,\operatorname{tr}(\cdot)\,$ is the trace. Starting from the aforementioned thermodynamic structure and without assuming any a priori specific form of $\,\psi\,$, show that $\,\alpha\,$ and $\,M\,$ can be expressed in terms of second derivatives of $\,\psi\,$ evaluated at the reference state.

Then, for the specific quadratic free energy
$$
\psi(\varepsilon, m)
\;=\;
\frac{1}{2}\,\kappa\,\big(\operatorname{tr}\varepsilon\big)^{2}
\;+\;
\mu\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{dev}}:\varepsilon_{\mathrm{dev}}
\;-\;
\beta\, m\,\operatorname{tr}\varepsilon
\;+\;
\frac{1}{2}\,n\, m^{2},
$$
with $\,\varepsilon_{\mathrm{dev}} := \varepsilon - \frac{1}{3}\operatorname{tr}\varepsilon\,\mathbf{I}\,$, $\,\kappa0\,$ (bulk modulus), $\,\mu0\,$ (shear modulus), $\,n0\,$, and $\,\beta\in\mathbb{R}\,$ chosen so that $\,\psi\,$ is strictly convex, compute $\,\alpha\,$ and $\,M\,$ explicitly in terms of $\,\beta\,$ and $\,n\,$. Express your final answer as exact analytic expressions. The final answer must be given as a row matrix containing first $\,\alpha\,$ and then $\,M\,$.
